\section*{Sleep Example}
MIT researchers examined the effect of melatonin on sleep.  Suppose that we know that men given a placebo fell asleep according to a N(15,5) distribution.  For each question below identify (i) the distribution that would be used, (ii) whether the question can be answered or not, (iii) specific characteristics of the required distribution, and (iv) if appropriate, the answer to the question.

\begin{Enumerate}
  \item What is the probability, with 4 randomly selected men, of observing a mean of more than 12 mins?
  \item What is the probability that a randomly selected man will fall asleep in more than 12 mins?
  \item What is the probability that 25 randomly selected will have a mean time to fall asleep of more than 15.5 minutes?
\end{Enumerate}

\section*{Pollutants in Auto Exhaust Example}
The level of nitrogen oxides (NOX) in the exhaust of a particular car model is right-skewed with a mean of 0.9 grams per mile (g/mi) and a standard deviation of 0.15 g/mi.  For each question below identify (i) the distribution that would be used, (ii) whether the question can be answered or not, (iii) specific characteristics of the required distribution, and (iv) if appropriate, the answer to the question.

\begin{Enumerate}
  \item What is the probability that a car will have a NOX greater than 1 g/mi?
  \item What is the probability that a random sample of 15 cars will have a mean NOX greater than 1 g/mi?
  \item What is the probability that a random sample of 50 cars will have a mean NOX greater than 1 g/mi?
  \item What is the probability that a random sample of 50 cars will have a mean NOX less than 0.8 g/mi?
  \item What is the mean NOX such that only 1\% of samples of 50 cars have a larger mean?
\end{Enumerate}

\section*{Acorn Example}
Suppose that it is known that the distribution of lengths of acorns is slightly right-skewed with a mean of 21 mm and a standard deviation of 6 mm.  For each question below identify (i) the distribution that would be used, (ii) whether the question can be answered or not, (iii) specific characteristics of the required distribution, and (iv) if appropriate, the answer to the question.

\begin{Enumerate}
  \item What is the probability that an acorn will have a length greater than 25 mm?
  \item What is the probability that the mean length of a sample of 25 acorns will be greater than 25 mm?
  \item	What is the probability that the mean length of a sample of 50 acorns will be between 20 and 25 mm?
  \item What is the probability that the mean length of a sample of 6 acorns will be less than 20 mm?
  \item What is the probability that an acorn will have a length less than 20 mm?
\end{Enumerate}

