\section*{People in Car Example}
A study of rush-hour traffic in San Francisco counted the number of people in a car entering a freeway at a suburban interchange.  Suppose that, in the population, this count has a mean of 1.5 people with a standard deviation of 0.75.

\begin{Enumerate}
  \item Do you expect this count to follow a normal distribution?  What are two pieces of evidence to support your answer?
  \item What is the probability that a random sample of 40 cars will have a mean number of passengers of less than 1.2?
  \item What is the probability that a random sample of 50 cars will have a mean number of passengers of greater than 2.0?
  \item What is the probability that a random sample of 5 cars will have a mean number of passengers of greater than 2.0?
  \item Suppose that 700 cars pass through this intersection in one hour.  What is the probability that these 700 cars will carry more than 1075 people?
\end{Enumerate}


\section*{Plowing Snow Example}
Supposed that it is know that the distribution of times spent plowing a city block on snow days is right-skewed with a mean of 45 seconds and a standard deviation of 28 seconds.
\begin{Enumerate}
  \item What is the probability that in a sample of 5 blocks that the mean is greater than 60 seconds?
  \item What is the probability that it will take longer than 60 seconds for one block?
  \item What is the probability that in a sample of 40 blocks will have a mean between 40 and 50 seconds?
  \item What is the Q1 for the mean plow time in samples of 40 blocks?
\end{Enumerate}

